# Copy to .env (or paste these into Dokploy's Environment settings).

# --- SSH access (paths 1 & 2: ssh + VS Code Remote-SSH) ---
# The AGENT account runs Claude Code and has NO sudo. One or more PUBLIC keys,
# newline-separated. Get yours with: cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
AUTHORIZED_KEYS="ssh-ed25519 AAAA... you@laptop"
# Optional password fallback for the `agent` user. Leave empty for key-only (recommended).
SSH_PASSWORD=""
# Host port Dokploy publishes for SSH (container listens on 22).
SSH_PUBLISH_PORT="2222"

# --- ADMIN account (human break-glass; FULL sudo for apt/system changes) ---
# Claude Code never uses this account. SSH in as `admin` to change the system.
# PUBLIC key(s), newline-separated. KEEP THIS KEY-ONLY: admin sudo is NOPASSWD,
# so an ADMIN_PASSWORD is effectively a root password.
ADMIN_AUTHORIZED_KEYS="ssh-ed25519 AAAA... you@laptop"
# Optional (discouraged) password login for `admin`. Leave empty for key-only.
ADMIN_PASSWORD=""

# --- code-server (path 3: browser VS Code) ---
# Password for the browser login screen. Leave empty only if you front it with Dokploy auth.
CODE_SERVER_PASSWORD="change-me-to-something-strong"

# --- Claude Code auth ---
# Deliberately NOT an env var: secrets in the container env can be read by the
# agent. Log in interactively after connecting:  claude
# (the token persists in the workspace-home volume). For non-interactive auth,
# see the apiKeyHelper approach in SECURITY.md.
